[12] USA (Washington State)
Date: 2 Apr 2014
Source: Voice of the Valley [edited]
http://www.voiceofthevalley.com/community_news/news/article_3f6ec7a6-baf3-11e3-90be-0017a43b2370.html


A person who was confirmed with measles traveled to several western Washington public locations while contagious. Most people in our state are immune to measles, so the public risk is low except for people who are unvaccinated. People who haven't been vaccinated or aren't sure whether they're immune should ask a health care professional for advice.

Public health officials say the Whatcom County woman in her 20s became contagious with measles on 26 Mar 2014 after visiting a local family with measles linked to an outbreak in British Columbia. She worked at the Lynden Dutch Bakery while contagious. Measles is highly contagious and can cause severe illness with rash, fever, cough, eye irritation, and can be fatal.

The woman traveled to Seattle for a Kings of Leon concert at Key Arena on 28 Mar 2014, when she also was at the Best Western Loyal Inn and the Wasabi Bistro. The next day, she was at Beth's Cafe, Aurora Suzuki, Starbucks at 1st and Pike, and the Pike Place Market. On those same dates, she visited several locations in Pierce County, including Celebrity Cake Studio, LeMay Car Museum, Harmon Brewing Company, and some department stores. A complete list of the locations and the times of potential public exposure are available online.

Anyone who was in those locations at the listed times should find out whether they have been vaccinated for measles or have had measles previously. People who are unvaccinated, who aren't sure whether they're immune, and who develop an illness with fever or unexplained rash should consult a health care professional immediately. Public health officials urge them to call ahead to their clinic, doctor's office, or emergency room before arriving so people in waiting rooms aren't exposed.

Measles is highly contagious even before the rash starts and is easily spread when an infected person breathes, coughs, or sneezes; if you're not vaccinated, you can get the measles just by walking into a room where someone with the disease has been in the past couple of hours.

Washington typically has 5 or fewer measles cases per year; so far in 2014, there have been 7. Symptoms begin 7-21 days after exposure, and an infected person is contagious for about 4 days before the rash appears until 4 days afterward. People at highest risk from exposure to measles include those who are unvaccinated, pregnant women, infants under 6 months of age and those with weakened immune systems.

Children should be vaccinated with 2 doses of measles, mumps, rubella vaccine, with the 1st dose between 12 and 15 months and the 2nd at 4-6 years. Adults should have at least one measles vaccination, with some people needing 2. The state Department of Health immunization program has more information about measles and measles vaccine.

In an unrelated situation, a single measles case in San Juan County has been confirmed, and health officials are working to contact people who may have been exposed. Information is available on the state health department website and online from San Juan County.

Also, a traveler from California passed through SeaTac Airport on 21-22 Mar 2014 while contagious with measles. Public Health - Seattle & King County is leading the investigation.

